Dalphin et al.

Page 7

that the client peptides could be visualized, given that DnaJ did not enter the gel. Independent experiments performed at pH 6.8, where DnaJ enters gels, showed consistent results (Figure S1). As reference information, the expected isoelectric point of DnaJ is 8.5.

Luciferase refolding assays in buffered solution.
Luciferase denaturation and refolding was carried as described,55 with the following minor modifications. Pure luciferase (8 μM, Promega) was unfolded in unfolding buffer (25 mM HEPES/KOH pH 7.6, 5 mM MgCl2, 50 mM KCl, 6 M guanidine hydrochloride (GdnHCl), 5 mM β-mercaptoethanol (BME)) at room temperature for one hr. Refolding was carried out at 30 °C for 1 hr after 400-fold dilution into a refolding buffer (25 mM HEPES/KOH pH 7.6, 5 mM MgCl2, 50 mM KCl, 5 mM BME, 2 mM ATP) containing variable amounts of KLR-70 peptide (0 − 400 μM). In some instances (see specific figures), the refolding buffer also contained DnaK, DnaJ and GrpE (0.6 μM, 0.12 μM and 0.24 μM, respectively). After 1 hr incubation, the refolding mixtures were then diluted 33-fold into Steady-Glo solution (Promega), and samples were transferred into a 96-well plate, followed by luminescence detection via an EnVision 2100 or EnVision 2105 microplate reader (Perkin Elmer) equipped with a < 700 nm shortpass filter.

Luciferase refolding assays in cell-free systems.
Luciferase unfolding was carried out as listed in the previous section. Refolding was performed at 30 °C for 1 hr after 150-fold dilution into an E. coli cell-free system identical to the one employed for protein expression with the following modifications. The cell-free system employed in luciferase refolding experiments included 2.6 mM ATP, 0.4 mM of other NTPs (e.g. GTP, CTP and UTP) and lacked both T7 RNA polymerase and BODIPY 576/589-Met-tRNAfMet. When specified, the cell-free systems also included S30 extract at 1.5-fold higher concentration. Some of the assays included cell-free systems lacking S30 extracts. These solutions are denoted as cell-free mixtures (c.f. mix) in this work. Some of the refolding solutions also contained additional amounts of chaperones, including DnaK, DnaJ and GrpE (at 0.6 μM, 0.12 μM and 0.24 μM, respectively) or GroEL and GroES (at 0.5 μM and 1.0 μM, respectively). After 1 hr incubation, the refolding mixtures were diluted 33fold into Steady-Glo solution (Promega), and samples were transferred into a 96-well plate, followed by luminescence detection via an EnVision 2100 or EnVision 2105 microplate reader (Perkin Elmer) equipped with a shortpass filter with 700 nm cut-off wavelength.

Data analysis of native gels to generate binding-isotherms.
Binding isotherms monitoring the affinity of KLR-70 for DnaK were generated as described in the section titled Native gels involving DnaK. Gel-band intensities were initially quantified with the ImageJ software.52, 53 A representative example is shown in panel A of Figure S2. Inspection of these intensity profiles highlights three challenging aspects of the ligand-binding data processing.
First, the peptide-bound and unbound states of DnaK are extremely poorly resolved on native gels even after extensive attempts of optimizing experimental conditions.

Author Manuscript

Author Manuscript

Biochemistry. Author manuscript; available in PMC 2021 July 30.

Author Manuscript

Author Manuscript

Dalphin et al.

Page 8

Second, the native gels exhibited subtle species-independent, random fluctuations in vertical band position.

Third, the ImageJ software is only able to produce discrete gel-band intensity values (e.g., see dotted traces in plot of panel A of Figure S2).

The above complications required the raw ImageJ traces to be carefully deconvoluted with continuous mathematical functions, and the data to correct for random vertical-height fluctuations. We achieved the above goals by a series of steps. First, we fit the raw ImageJ data to sums of Gaussians via the MATLAB software package (The MathWorks Inc. Natick, MA, v. R2016b). The Gaussian curves were used in all downstream analysis, in place of the ImageJ raw band intensities. Then, we carried out gel-band deconvolution followed by mathematical realignment. Representative examples of the above procedure are shown in panels B – D of Figure S2.

Gel band intensities of DnaK samples lacking KLR-70 were fit to an unconstrained sum of two Gaussians (see panel B of Figure S2) according to

I(d)0μM = a1, 0μMe −

d−b1, 0μM 2 c1, 0μM

+ a2, 0μMe −

d−b2, 0μM c2, 0μM

2
,

(1)

where I(d)0 μM denotes the gel band intensity, which is a function of migration distance (d) for DnaK samples lacking KLR-70 (0 μM). In addition, the a, b and c terms denote amplitude, mean value and width of the Gaussian curves, respectively. The Gaussian curves represent intensity distributions of the top (distribution 1) and bottom (distribution 2) nativegel bands, likely representing different conformational states of DnaK. Gel band intensities of samples containing varied KLR-70 concentrations (X μM) were fit to constrained models which forced the bottom band Gaussians to have the same difference in mean migration distances as the samples lacking KLR-70 as shown in panel B of Figure S2, according to

I(d)XμM = a2, XμMe −

d−b2, XμM c2, XμM

2

+ a1, XμMe −

d− b2, XμM − b2, 0μM − b1, 0μM c1, XμM

2
.

(2)

The resulting Gaussians accurately represent gel-band intensity profiles for the peptideunbound and -bound states of DnaK (r2 ≥ 0.98 for all samples). Next, the Gaussians were adjusted so that all curves within the same gel had their top and bottom Gaussians overlap, to account for lane-dependent small random migration differences through the native gel (see panel C of Figure S2), according to

I(d)XμM, adjusted = a2, XμMe −

d−b2, 0μM c2, XμM

2

+ a1, XμMe −

d−b1, 0μM c1, XμM

2

.

(3)

Finally, the adjusted Gaussians had their total areas normalized to 1 to correct for small errors due to different total sample amounts loaded onto different gel lanes.

