Once the above procedure was complete, the increase in the bottom DnaK-band (termed “DnaK band 2”) intensity upon addition of KLR-70 was plotted and fit to a mathematical model in Origin (OriginLab Corporation, v. 2018b) to determine their dissociation constant (see panel D of Figure S2).

The direct binding of KLR-70 to DnaK was modeled as a simple two-state process shown below,

D+P DP,

(4)

where D, P and DP denote DnaK, KLR-70 peptide and DnaK-KLR-70 complex, respectively. The dissociation constant for the direct binding of KLR-70 to DnaK (KD1) can be written as

KD1

=

DeqPeq DPeq

,

(5)

with Deq, Peq and DPeq,KLR−70 denoting the equilibrium concentrations of DnaK, KLR-70 and DnaK-KLR-70 complex. Equation 5 can be recast as

KD1 =

D0 − fB1D0 P0 − fB1D0 fB1D0

,

(6)

where D0 and P0 denote the total concentrations of DnaK and KLR-70 and fB1 denotes the fraction of KLR-70-bound directly to DnaK. Equation 6 can be further simplified to solve for fB1. The only physically meaningful solution of the resulting quadratic equation is

fB1

= KD1 + D0 + P0, KLR − 70 −

KD1 + D0 + P0, KLR − 70 2 − 4 D0P0, KLR − 70 2D0

.

(7)

Equation 7 can be substituted directly into the following expression which describes how the observed maximum normalized gel band intensity of DnaK band 2 (Iobs) varies with fB1:

Iobs = fB1Ibound + 1 − fB1 Ifree ,

(8)

where I free and Ibound are the maximum normalized gel band intensities of DnaK band 2 under fully-free and fully-bound conditions.

Experimental data points were then fit to equation 8, after replacement of equation 7 into it,, with KD1, Ifree and Ibound serving as the adjustable parameters. Data are reported as an average KD1 from n = 3 independent experiments ± standard error.

Steady-state fluorescence anisotropy: data collection and analysis to generate binding isotherms.
Experiments monitoring the binding of the KLR-70 peptide for ADP-DnaK via fluorescence anisotropy were carried out either in direct-binding or competitive-inhibition modes. In both

